[4] Cholera - Congo DR (Kwilu, South Kivu)
Date: Fri 18 Aug 2017
Source: Voice of America (VOA) News, Afrique, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.voaafrique.com/a/seize-morts-du-cholera-en-une-semaine-dans-le-sud-ouest-de-la-rdc/3991609.html


A total of 16 people died of cholera in one week in a region in the south west of the Democratic Republic of the Congo [DRC], where about 100 cases have been recorded, it was learned [Fri 18 Aug 2017] from the provincial authorities.

"We have recorded 16 cases of deaths and about 100 people are infected with cholera" in 3 zones of the province of Kwilu, governor Nicholas Bulukungu told reporters. "The province does not have a center specializing in the treatment of cholera. The isolation of the patients is a serious problem," he said. The town of Bandundu and the 2 affected localities are inhabited by nearly a million people, invited to "strict observance of the basic rules of hygiene."

Another Congolese province (South Kivu in the east) is facing an outbreak of cholera with 2 deaths and several tens of cases reported for nearly 3 weeks.

According to the UN, cholera has become a major public health problem in the DRC with thousands of cases recorded every year in many provinces in this vast country without infrastructure and where most of the population lives in poverty.

More than 700 deaths of cholera were recorded in 2016 in the DRC.

